excerpt: Museum in the 19th-century home of a Civil War soldier's family, exploring the civilian experience.
detail_description: The Shriver House Museum is a historic site located in Gettysburg, Pennsylvania. It was the 19th-century home of a Civil War soldier's family and offers an immersive experience into the civilian life during and after the battle. The house, originally built with an adjacent building for a saloon and bowling alley, has been restored to its period accuracy. Visitors can take a guided tour to learn about the Shriver family's experiences during those fateful days in July.
name: Shriver House Museum at Gettysburg

excerpt: Museum dedicated to Gettysburg civilian casualty Jennie Wade with exhibits on domestic wartime life.
detail_description: The Jennie Wade House in Gettysburg is a museum dedicated to the memory of Jennie Wade, a civilian casualty during the Civil War. The house offers exhibits on domestic wartime life and tells the poignant story of Jennie's untimely death. Preserved just as it looked in 1863, each room reflects the sudden shift from normal life during those three days.
name: Jennie Wade House Museum

excerpt: Museum with interactive exhibits dedicated to the Battle of Gettysburg, plus cupola tours.
detail_description: The Seminary Ridge Museum and Education Center is housed in Schmucker Hall, a historic building with a significant role in the Battle of Gettysburg. Visitors can explore interactive exhibits dedicated to the battle and its aftermath. One of the main attractions is the opportunity to climb to the open-air cupola, offering panoramic views similar to those seen by Union General John Buford on the eve of the battle.
name: Seminary Ridge Museum and Education Center
address: Valentine Hall, 61 Seminary Ridge, Gettysburg, PA 17325, USA

excerpt: Cozy rooms with 19th-century style in a historic B&B with an American alehouse & a restaurant.
detail_description: Step into the 19th-century charm of Dobbin House Tavern, a historic bed and breakfast featuring cozy rooms and an American alehouse. Originally built for Reverend Alexander Dobbin, this establishment is now a premier Gettysburg attraction. The candlelit elegance of the restaurant offers superior food and gracious service that transports guests back in time. The Springhouse Tavern provides a more intimate dining experience, while the Abigail Adams Ballroom caters to larger gatherings.
name: Dobbin House Tavern

excerpt: Museum explaining the results & aftermath of the Battle of Gettysburg & President Lincoln's address.
detail_description: The David Wills House, situated on Lincoln Square in Gettysburg, is a museum that offers insights into the aftermath of the Battle of Gettysburg and President Lincoln's historic address. Managed by the National Park Service since 2009, this historical site showcases exhibits about the local community, the Gettysburg National Cemetery, and Lincoln's visit. Visitors can explore two rooms restored to their late 1863 appearance, including the bedroom where Lincoln stayed and finalized his speech.
name: David Wills House

excerpt: Resting place for 3,512 Union soldiers, dedicated in 1863 with Lincoln's Gettysburg Address.
detail_description: Gettysburg National Cemetery is a solemn resting place for 3,512 Union soldiers and was dedicated in 1863 with Lincoln's Gettysburg Address. The area offers a glimpse into the challenging conditions faced by soldiers during the Civil War, carrying heavy loads and enduring harsh elements. Visitors can explore the roughly 3-mile Gettysburg Trail, a paved walking trail that connects the Visitor Center to important battlefield locations, offering serene woodland surroundings and welcome shade on hot days.
name: Gettysburg National Cemetery
address: National Park Service Museum and Visitor Center, 1195 Baltimore Pike, Gettysburg, PA 17325, USA

excerpt: More than 4,000 artifacts chronicling various American wars with several exhibits & a gift shop.
detail_description: The Gettysburg Museum of History is a treasure trove for history enthusiasts, boasting over 4,000 artifacts spanning various American wars and historical periods. From a Confederate flag used at the First Battle of Bull Run to former President Abraham Lincoln's wallet, the museum offers an eclectic collection that includes an Egyptian mummy head, Saddam Hussein's dining set, and Adolf Hitler's footstool.
name: Gettysburg Museum of History

excerpt: Historical spot with self-guided tours features a re-creation of the Battle of Gettysburg & more.
detail_description: The Gettysburg Heritage Center is a historical site that offers self-guided tours and aims to educate visitors about the Battle of Gettysburg. Through artifacts, documents, and interactive displays, the center provides insight into the impact of the battle on the community. It features unique accounts of how locals experienced one of the Civil War's most significant battles near their homes and farms.
name: Gettysburg Heritage Center

excerpt: Diorama of the Battle of Gettysburg with over 20,000 pieces, plus a 30-minute light & audio show.
detail_description: The Gettysburg Diorama is an extraordinary attraction that brings the historic Battle of Gettysburg to life through a stunning miniature display. Comprising over 20,000 meticulously hand-painted figures, including soldiers, horses, and cannons, this diorama offers a comprehensive view of the entire 6,000-acre battlefield. Visitors can immerse themselves in a captivating 30-minute light and audio show that narrates the dramatic events of the three-day battle from start to finish.
name: Gettysburg Diorama & History Center

excerpt: Gettysburg is a borough and town in the U.S. state of Pennsylvania. It’s known for Gettysburg National Battlefield, site of a turning point in the Civil War, now part of Gettysburg National Military Park. The park also includes the Gettysburg Museum and Visitor Center, displaying Civil War artifacts, and Gettysburg National Cemetery, where a memorial marks the site of Abraham Lincoln’s 1863 Gettysburg Address.
detail_description: Gettysburg, located in Pennsylvania, is famous for the Gettysburg National Battlefield, a pivotal site in the Civil War. The battlefield is part of the Gettysburg National Military Park and features the Gettysburg Museum and Visitor Center as well as the Gettysburg National Cemetery, where Abraham Lincoln delivered his historic address in 1863. Additionally, there are accommodations like Battlefield Bed and Breakfast Inn that offer a romantic retreat with various room options.
name: Gettysburg

excerpt: Handmade dioramas with cat soldiers depict key battles & scenes in a historic former orphanage.
detail_description: Discover the unique and historically accurate dioramas at Civil War Tails at the Homestead Diorama Museum, where handmade miniature cat soldiers depict key battles and scenes from the Civil War. This museum offers a fascinating look into this pivotal period in American history, showcasing weaponry, uniforms, and personal effects from both sides of the conflict. Visitors can also explore other nearby attractions such as Mister Ed's Elephant Museum & Candy Emporium and the Eastern Museum of Motor Racing for a well-rounded experience.
name: Civil War Tails at the Homestead Diorama Museum

detail_description: Savor Gettysburg Food Tours offers a delightful three-hour walking tour that takes you through historic streets, showcasing cultural highlights and introducing you to seven unique eateries. Suitable for all fitness levels, the tour covers about one mile and includes visits to an old historic tavern, an exotic ethnic restaurant, a family-owned bistro, and more.
name: Savor Gettysburg Food Tours

excerpt: Museum displaying model trains & layouts, along with artifacts related to Abraham Lincoln.
detail_description: The Lincoln Train Museum in Gettysburg is a must-visit for railroad enthusiasts and history buffs alike. It showcases the significant connections between Abraham Lincoln and trains, highlighting their role during his presidency. Visitors can experience the 'Lincoln Train Ride' and explore the Lincoln Toy Train collection with over 1000 trains and Civil War dioramas. The museum also offers an extensive array of railway memorabilia, historical documents, and Gettysburg souvenirs at the Station Masters gift shop.
name: Lincoln Train Museum

excerpt: Historic theater space with retro charm offers live music acts, musicals, comedians & classic films.
detail_description: The Majestic Theater, a historic venue with a retro allure, has been hosting live music acts, musicals, comedians, and classic films since its opening in 1925. Once the largest vaudeville and silent movie theater in south-central Pennsylvania, it gained fame in the 1950s when President Dwight D. Eisenhower and his wife Mamie frequented performances there.
name: Majestic Theater

detail_description: Ronn Palm's Museum of Civil War Images is a unique attraction in downtown Gettysburg, featuring a vast private collection of photographs from the American Civil War. This quirky museum is ideal for history buffs and those interested in historical photography. Visitors can explore thousands of images capturing glimpses of the Battle of Gettysburg and other significant moments from that era. The owner, Ronn Palm, is known for his extensive knowledge and willingness to share insights about the items on display.
name: Ronn Palm's Museum of Civil War Images

detail_description: Explore the historic Gettysburg Battlefield on horseback with Confederate Trails of Gettysburg Guided Horseback Tours. Ride through tranquil wooded paths and open to panoramic views of history, feeling transported back in time as you follow the Confederate lines with knowledgeable staff. The well-behaved and responsive horses make for a gentle ride, enhancing the experience of learning about the battle.
name: Confederate Trails of Gettysburg Guided Horseback Tours
address: Youth Group Campground Entrance McMillian Woods Youth Campground GNMP, W Confederate Ave, Gettysburg, PA 17325, USA

detail_description: The Adams County Winery Gettysburg Wine Shop is a must-visit destination for wine enthusiasts in downtown Gettysburg. As the oldest winery in the area, it has been producing award-winning wines since 1975, with grapes grown on the picturesque South Mountains overlooking Gettysburg. Visitors can enjoy tastings at the post Civil War era barn on-site or stop by the downtown wine shop while exploring the city's shopping scene.
name: Adams County Winery Gettysburg Wine Shop

detail_description: Nestled in the lively area of Lincoln Square, The Inn at Lincoln Square offers a cozy retreat in the heart of town. Located within walking distance to the Gettysburg Battlefield and surrounded by local nightlife and activities, this Georgian-style inn provides various accommodation options. Downtown Gettysburg is brimming with shops, boutiques, cafes, and restaurants leading up to historic Lincoln Square. Visitors can explore an array of offerings from clothing and fine arts to collectibles and home decor.
name: Lincoln Square

detail_description: The Children of Gettysburg 1863 museum offers an educational and engaging experience for kids, providing a child-friendly perspective on the Battle of Gettysburg. The exhibits allow children to empathize with the experiences of young people during the Civil War, incorporating interactive elements to maintain their interest. Located in the historic Rupp House, which was home to a family during the battle, this museum shares compelling stories of children and young adults from that time.
name: Children of Gettysburg 1863®

detail_description: Gettysburg Beyond the Battle Museum, opened in April 2023, offers a fresh perspective on the town and its famous battle. The museum's 12 galleries focus on the stories of local residents before, during, and after the Civil War. It honors the sacrifices made while celebrating the heroics of civilians who rebuilt the town. Visitors can explore exhibits, artifacts, short films, and immersive experiences that provide insight into life in Adams County during and after the battle.
name: Gettysburg Beyond the Battle Museum

detail_description: Gettysburg Battlefield, also known as the Gettysburg National Military Park, is a significant historical site that played a pivotal role in the Civil War. The battlefield offers free self-guided tours across its 9,000-acre expanse and provides various guided tour options for visitors. One notable area within the battlefield is Lee’s Headquarters, also referred to as the 143rd's Last Stand.
name: Gettysburg Battlefield: Lee’s Headquarters

detail_description: Gettysburg Ghost Tours offers an outdoor experience, so wearing comfortable shoes and weather-appropriate clothing is recommended. The tour is not suitable for children under 14. The knowledgeable and hospitable staff provide a fun and unique time, but the paranormal nature of the tour can make it a harrowing experience. The tours do not enter cemeteries or the battlefield due to federal property restrictions, but they offer different special spots and provide historical stories along with ghostly encounters.
name: Gettysburg Ghost Tours

excerpt: Headquarters & meeting place for spooky walking tours around Gettysburg's haunted landmarks.
detail_description: Mark Nesbitt's Ghosts of Gettysburg Candlelight Walking Tours is the headquarters for spooky walking tours around the haunted landmarks of Gettysburg. The guided walking tours offer a unique way to explore the town's history, including civilian experiences during and after the Battle of Gettysburg and President Lincoln's visit for the dedication of the National Cemetery. The tours can be tailored to cover various historical periods, making them suitable for all ages.
name: Mark Nesbitt's Ghosts of Gettysburg Candlelight Walking Tours

detail_description: Ghostly Images of Gettysburg offers nightly 90-minute walking tours that take visitors inside the Jennie Wade House or Haunted Orphanage, both known for their ghostly activity. The Haunted Orphanage is particularly chilling, as it was once a place where innocent children suffered at the hands of a cruel matron. These locations have been featured on popular television shows and attract many brave souls. In addition to regular tours, Ghostly Images also offers specialty tours throughout the year.
name: Ghostly Images of Gettysburg

excerpt: Beer flights & drafts, plus hearty pub grub, offered in a rustic haunt with TVs & outdoor seats.
detail_description: Fourscore Beer Co. is a rustic spot in Gettysburg, an offshoot of the well-known Tommys Pizza. It opened its doors in July 2019 and offers a rotating menu with a variety of well-crafted beers like Hop Hat IPA, Gettys Brau pilsner, and The Lincolnator German doppelbock.
name: Fourscore Beer Co.
address: 603 S Washington St, Gettysburg, PA 17325, USA

excerpt: Over 20 Irish whiskies, draft beers & traditional Irish fare along with weekly live music.
detail_description: Garryowen Irish Pub is a popular spot known for its authentic Irish atmosphere and cuisine. The pub offers a wide selection of over 100 Irish whiskies, along with draft beers and traditional Irish dishes. Guests can indulge in classics like Scotch eggs, shepherd's pie, and Ulster fry, as well as innovative creations such as grilled hot whiskey sausage sandwiches and Irish nachos loaded with crispy potatoes, cheese, bacon, tomatoes, jalapenos, and scallions.
name: Garryowen Irish Pub

detail_description: The Soldiers' National Cemetery in Gettysburg, Pennsylvania, is a historic site that holds great significance as the final resting place for over 3,000 Union soldiers who perished during the Battle of Gettysburg. This hallowed ground was dedicated by President Abraham Lincoln in his iconic Gettysburg Address on November 19, 1863. The cemetery and battlefield are adorned with numerous monuments honoring both Union and Confederate troops who fought in this pivotal battle.
name: Soldiers' National Cemetery

detail_description: Seminary Ridge is a significant feature in the Gettysburg Battlefield, offering a long north-south ridge with an elevation of 60 feet above the surrounding area. Visitors can enjoy stunning vistas from landmarks like Little Round Top and Big Round Top, which provide views across Devils Den and Eisenhower Farm.
name: Seminary Ridge

detail_description: If you're a fan of the historical theme, 1863 Escape Room is definitely worth checking out. The escape room is themed around the Battle of Gettysburg and is very well designed and challenging. The staff are very friendly and helpful, making it a great experience for groups.
name: 1863 Escape Room

detail_description: Gettysburg Ghost Tours by Civil War Ghosts offers a variety of tours, from family-friendly walks to thrilling paranormal adventures. You can even try the Ghosts of Gettysburg Scavenger Hunt for your own ghost hunt experience. Join the tour to hear gripping stories of the ghosts and hauntings from the decisive battle of the Civil War.
name: Gettysburg Ghosts Tours & Haunted Pub Crawls

detail_description: Steinwehr Ave is a lesser-known shopping district in Gettysburg, located near Lincoln Square. While Lincoln Square and its surrounding streets are popular among visitors, Steinwehr Ave offers a unique shopping experience that is often overlooked. It's easily accessible from the parking garage and also provides on-street metered parking for those who prefer to move their car closer to the shops.
name: Steinwehr Ave

detail_description: Evergreen Cemetery, established in 1854 by Civil War survivor David McConaughy, is a historic resting place for notable figures like theologian Samuel S. Schmucker and Congressman Edward McPherson. It also holds the grave of Jennie Wade, the only civilian killed in the Battle of Gettysburg. The cemetery is a significant site filled with history related to the battle and local townspeople.
name: Evergreen Cemetery

detail_description: Reid's Winery Tasting Room and Cider House, located in the picturesque orchards and vineyards of Pennsylvania, offers a delightful experience for wine and cider enthusiasts. The tasting room features an array of wines from full-bodied reds to sweet options, as well as a rotating selection of ciders made from locally grown berries and apples. Visitors can also enjoy tours of the winery, craft brewery experiences, live music events on weekends, and relax in the sunroom or wine garden.
name: Reid's Winery Tasting Room and Cider House

detail_description: The Battlefield Military Museum is a great place to see actual war items. The owner and his son really enjoy what they have.
name: Battlefield Military Museum

detail_description: The Gettysburg Tour Center, operated by Gettysburg Tours, Inc., offers popular battlefield tours on open-air double-decker buses or enclosed air-conditioned coaches. Visitors can explore the historic fields of Gettysburg during the two-hour bus tours and gain insights into the national and international politics of the time. The tour guides are known for their informative and witty commentary, providing a great way to learn about Gettysburg.
name: Gettysburg Tour Center

detail_description: Gallery 30 is a renowned stop for those with a taste for fine art and crafts, featuring works from local and regional artists, authors, and artisans. The gallery has built a reputation for offering high-quality hand-crafted American products. Visitors can explore the developed commercial area surrounding Gallery 30 to enjoy a great shopping experience at various stores. Customers have praised the store's unique and cool items, including home decor, holiday decorations, books, clothing, gifts, and jewelry.
name: Gallery 30

detail_description: Located in Gettysburg, The Christmas Haus is a charming store that offers an array of authentic German Christmas decorations. Visitors can explore a wide selection of items such as German glass ornaments, nutcrackers, smokers, and other festive decor. The shop is known for its beautiful and intricately crafted figurines and decorations. Customers have praised the helpful staff who assist in finding specific items like feathered ornaments.
name: The Christmas Haus

excerpt: Gettysburg Battlefield B&B with country-style rooms & a garden, plus free WiFi & a hot breakfast.
name: Doubleday Inn

detail_description: The Sleepy Hollow of Gettysburg Candlelight Ghost Tours offers an immersive experience with knowledgeable guides who have been working there for over 50 years. The tour guides wear old-time costumes and speak in accents, adding to the authenticity of the experience. Visitors can take a cellar tour with Doc, who provides interesting historical insights about the house and Gettysburg, along with personal supernatural stories. Guests also praise other guides like Ken and Tiffany for their detailed storytelling and engaging personalities during the tours.
name: Sleepy Hollow of Gettysburg Candlelight Ghost Tours

detail_description: The Adams County Farmers Market, located in Lincoln Square, is a vibrant hub of local food and crafts. Open every Saturday morning from the end of April to the end of October, it offers an array of products including fruits, flowers, baked goods, cheeses, and hand-crafted art. Visitors can also enjoy Amish baked goods and fresh produce while taking in the lively atmosphere.
name: Adams County Farmers Market

excerpt: Hip Gettysburg Hotel hub with historic flair making updated American comfort food & craft cocktails.
detail_description: One Lincoln is a trendy restaurant located in the historic Gettysburg Hotel, offering a blend of modern American comfort food and craft cocktails. The interior exudes a cosmopolitan vibe, with an upscale yet family-friendly ambiance. Executive chef Joseph Holmes leads the culinary team in preparing traditional American dishes and fresh seafood for breakfast, lunch, and dinner. The restaurant's prime location on Lincoln Square provides both indoor and outdoor seating with picturesque views.
name: One Lincoln

excerpt: New American eats & craft cocktails are the specialties at this relaxed venue with a laid–back vibe.
detail_description: This American restaurant in Gettysburg offers a relaxed atmosphere with specialties including eats and cocktails. The venue accepts American Express, accepts Mastercard, and accepts Visa. There is outdoor seating as well as parking available.
name: Mason Dixon Distillery
address: 331 E Water St, Gettysburg, PA 17325, USA

detail_description: Haunted Gettysburg Ghost Tours offers an unforgettable experience for those intrigued by the supernatural. Nestled in the historic town of Gettysburg, Pennsylvania, this tour invites guests to delve into a world filled with ghostly tales and eerie encounters. Visitors can expect to hear spine-chilling stories about apparitions from the Civil War era, including sightings of Confederate soldiers and mysterious figures like a woman in white who roams the grounds at night.
name: Haunted Gettysburg Ghost Tours

detail_description: The Gettysburg Battlefield Driving Tour is a popular and romantic activity for visitors, offering the chance to explore historic sites and picturesque countryside. Many families have had wonderful experiences on this tour, admiring artwork, sculptures, and natural beauty while feeling the emotional energy of the place. The tour provides valuable information about the battle's history through audio guides and ranger lectures. Visitors can go at their own pace, making stops to take pictures and fully absorb the experience.
name: Gettysburg Battlefield Driving Tour
address: Heritage Center’s parking, lot 297 Steinwehr Ave, Gettysburg, PA 17325, USA

excerpt: Open, airy brewery serves housemade beers & craft sodas alongside burgers & other casual bites.
detail_description: The Appalachian Brewing Company of Gettysburg - Battlefield is a spacious and airy brewery that offers a wide selection of housemade beers and craft sodas, as well as a menu featuring casual bites such as burgers and classic bar fare. Established in 1997 in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, this brewery has expanded to five other towns, including the Gettysburg Battlefield location situated near the Gettysburg Heritage Center.
name: Appalachian Brewing Company of Gettysburg - Battlefield

detail_description: Upper Crust is a delicious retro-themed pizza restaurant that is great for atmosphere and service. The food is delicious and the ingredients are fresh. They have a variety of toppings to choose from, so there's sure to be something for everyone. The only downside may be that their pizzas are a bit on the done side - but that's just a personal preference.
name: The Upper Crust

detail_description: If you're on the hunt for eerie experiences in Gettysburg, look no further than the Museum of Haunted Objects. This captivating venue showcases a diverse collection of haunted artifacts from around the world, including Ouija boards, cursed typewriters, and enigmatic dolls that might just send shivers down your spine. It’s like stepping into a chilling attic filled with stories waiting to be uncovered!
name: Museum of Haunted Objects

detail_description: Culp's Hill is one of the high points in Gettysburg National Military Park, along with Big Round Top, Little Round Top, and East Cemetery Hill. It played a crucial role in the Battle of Gettysburg as part of the Union defense line that formed the 'fishhook' shape. The hill offers a great vantage point to understand the scale and scope of the battlefield.
name: Culp's Hill
address: Culp's Hill Observation Tower, Culps Hill, Gettysburg, PA 17325, USA

excerpt: Iconic Civil War battlefield with scenic trails & an indoor museum dedicated to the war.
detail_description: Gettysburg National Military Park Museum & Visitor Center is a must-visit destination for history enthusiasts. The visitor center is the perfect starting point, offering helpful staff and an insightful overview of the battlefield and war history. The museum houses authentic artifacts that evoke the emotions of the battlefields, providing a profound understanding of the past. Visitors can also explore well-marked trails leading to outdoor battle sites even after the center closes.
name: Gettysburg National Military Park Museum & Visitor Center

excerpt: Tranquil former home of President Eisenhower offers tours, military exhibits & a kids programs.
detail_description: Eisenhower National Historic Site is the tranquil former home of President Eisenhower, offering tours, military exhibits, and kids programs. The majority of items in the house belonged to the Eisenhower family and remain as they were during their last days there. The introduction, house tour, and grounds are free with available parking on site. This historic spot provides insight into Post-World War II America and broader Gettysburg history.
name: Eisenhower National Historic Site
address: 243 Eisenhower Farm Rd, Gettysburg, PA 17325, USA
